Mushroom Edibility

Brooke Seibert

2/18/2019

Business Understanding

Project Overview

There is no simple rule for determining the edibility of a mushroom. Despite the risk, mushroom hunting is growing in popularity. The UCI Machine Learning repository created a dataset in 1987 about mushrooms. Although the dataset is older, the data is still relevant today for mushroom hunting. Each mushroom record is identified as edible, poisonous, or of unknown edibility and not recommended to consume. Therefore, this data can be used in a classification problem to attempt to better categorize mushroom species as being edible or poisonous to reduce the risk of mushroom hunters misclassifying and consuming poisonous mushrooms.

Business Questions

• What types of classification perform best on this dataset?
• Which features are most indicative of a poisonous mushroom?
• Are there any unique features that only poisonous or edible mushrooms have?

Data Understanding

Data Source

To further describe the data, the dataset was found through Kaggle as a CSV file with 8,124 records and 23 fields (https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/mushroom-classification/version/1#_=_). The mushroom records correspond to 23 gilled mushrooms species in the Agaricus and Lepiota Mushroom Family from the Audubon Society Field Guide to North American Mushrooms.
